# No explicit `: void` return types

Do not annotate functions with an explicit `: void` return type when TypeScript can infer it from the body.

```typescript
// Good — caller handles fire-and-forget and errors
askLlmToIdentifyInterests(userPrompt, assistantResponse, source).catch((error) => {
  logTurnError('interests identification failed', error, { source });
});

function logLiveRequestStart(contextLabel: string, request: TracedRequest) {
  console.log(contextLabel, request);
}

// Bad — redundant annotation
export function runAfterTurn(...): void {
  askLlmToIdentifyInterests(...).catch(handleError);
}
```

Keep explicit return types when they carry information TypeScript cannot infer (for example `Promise<string>`, `AgentLoopResult`, union types).

`Promise<void>` and callback types like `() => void` in type positions are fine; this rule applies only to function/method return type annotations. For the `void` operator on expressions, see `no-void-operator.mdc`.
